<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-545-934  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 545 934.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>UNIX World  June 1990 v7 n6 p86(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Less filling OLTP light. (UNIX systems for on-line transactionprocessing)(includes related articles on keynote address at UNIXExpo, problems of UNIx in handling OLTP)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Tucker, Michael Jay.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Unix systems are well-suited for many new on-line transactionprocessing (OLTP) applications that do not require a mainframe,such as relational data base management systems.andP;  UNIX has nottraditionally been successful in in OLTP because it was notdesigned to support OLTP requirements.andP;  It is a modular, flexibleoperating system whose database manager is outside the operatingsystem kernel, but vendors of database software have written RDBMSprograms that compensate for the UNIX kernel's lack offunctionality.andP;  UNIX systems can now handle applications thatrequire fault tolerance, high transaction volumes and relativelystrong data security at less cost than traditional mainframesolutions.andP;  Many UNIX OLTP users are new to the technology.andO;Organizations that now run UNIX OLTP include the Phar-Mor Incpharmacy chain and the US Employment Standards Administration.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     On-Line Transaction ProcessingOn-LineUNIXMinicomputersWorkstationsSystem Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   OLTP, Unix, and mainframes. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>